## Section 3: What the Data Challenges — Common Assumptions

### Budget Does Not Predict Performance

Perhaps the most significant finding is that budget has virtually no linear correlation with any performance metric. Spending more does not reliably produce more impressions, more clicks, more conversions, or higher ROI.

This does not mean budget is irrelevant — it means that how budget is allocated matters far more than how much is allocated. Two campaigns with identical budgets can produce dramatically different outcomes depending on channel selection, audience quality, and creative execution.

**Strategic implication:** Budget decisions should follow performance data, not precede it. The question should shift from "How much should we spend?" to "Which channels and audiences yield the best ROI per interaction?"

### CPC Is a Poor Performance Predictor

Cost per click shows near-zero correlation with both conversions and ROI. High CPC does not indicate high-quality traffic. Low CPC does not guarantee profitable returns. Some expensive clicks convert well; many cheap clicks do not convert at all.

Optimizing purely for low CPC risks prioritizing volume over quality and can actively reduce campaign efficiency.

### CTR and Conversion Rate Are Largely Independent

CTR shows negligible correlation with conversion rate (r = 0.005). This is a meaningful disconnect: a campaign can achieve a strong click-through rate while still failing to convert users into customers. High engagement at the ad level does not guarantee alignment with purchase intent.

This finding points to a common failure point — clicks arrive, but the post-click experience (landing page, offer, checkout flow) does not complete the conversion. Driving more traffic to a poorly optimized destination is unlikely to resolve this gap.

### ROI Operates Independently

ROI shows near-zero correlation with every other metric in the dataset. This suggests that profitability is shaped by variables not captured in standard traffic and engagement KPIs — likely factors such as revenue per conversion, customer lifetime value, product margin, and fixed operational costs. Single-metric optimization is unlikely to reliably drive ROI improvement without also addressing these underlying revenue dynamics.

